WOMAN: Out.

11:24.450 --> 11:25.685 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOMAN: Out.

11:25.718 --> 11:28.254 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: Definitely out. OK. Do
you want to
talk about it?

11:28.288 --> 11:29.923 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WOMAN: Shut that bloody channel
tunnel up,
mate.

11:29.956 --> 11:30.790 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOMAN: Really?

11:30.823 --> 11:31.357 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: Yes, absolutely, concrete
it up.

11:31.391 --> 11:31.758 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOMAN: OK.

11:31.791 --> 11:32.725 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
WOMAN: Yes.

11:32.759 --> 11:36.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: I think (INAUDIBLE) for
our country.

11:36.496 --> 11:41.701 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
MALCOLM BRABANT: But her
suggestion that immigration
made the country's foundation
stronger met

11:41.734 --> 11:43.636 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a sharp response.

11:43.670 --> 11:50.009 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WOMAN: My husband served 27
years in the military,
and what have we got to show for
it? Nothing.

11:50.043 --> 11:56.783 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fighting to keep them out,
definitely out,
absolutely, 100 percent, 100
percent out.

11:56.816 --> 12:03.089 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
My dad, his dad, my grandparents
all fought
to keep this country British.

12:03.122 --> 12:11.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: So, is Britain
about to chime
in with a painful divorce, after
an often

12:11.798 --> 12:17.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
turbulent, fractious, and
skeptical 43-year
union with her neighbors across
the North

12:17.704 --> 12:20.506 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Sea, and declare independence
day?

12:20.540 --> 12:25.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At this gentle summer garden
party in the
village of Hoxne, in amongst the
cream teas,

12:25.845 --> 12:29.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one of the key referendum issues
reared its
head in an almost visceral
manner.

12:30.016 --> 12:32.518 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
PETER LOCKETT, Retired
Electrician: I think
we should stop immigration and
not allow any

12:32.552 --> 12:37.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more people in the country. I
think there's
far too many as well pinching
our money for

12:37.123 --> 12:39.025 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
national health and all that
sort of thing.

12:39.058 --> 12:44.397 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Next to the
sausage stand,
the conversation switched to
national sovereignty

12:44.430 --> 12:49.869 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and the deep resentment many
Britons feel
about the amount of control
exerted by unelected

12:49.902 --> 12:53.339 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
European commissioners and their
unaccountable
staff in Brussels.

12:53.373 --> 12:58.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STUART JARROLD, Sports Reporter:
Every year,
every day, every hour, we are
spending so

12:58.044 --> 13:03.850 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
much money with faceless
individuals who -- we
can't even govern ourselves. Why
can't we,

13:03.883 --> 13:05.652 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as a nation, run our own
country?

13:05.685 --> 13:08.521 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ANTHONY BENTON, Great Britain:
In the long
run, if the human race is going
to exist to

13:08.554 --> 13:13.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
survive on this planet that
we're wrecking,
then we need to come together
and work together.

13:13.593 --> 13:20.166 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Karon Saunders
is a truly
international woman with part
Italian heritage

13:20.199 --> 13:26.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who's worked around the world.
But she will
vote to leave. She says
excessive E.U. regulation

13:26.372 --> 13:31.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is endangering her small organic
free-range
farm. She struggles to get her
animals into

13:31.944 --> 13:37.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
abattoirs that favor industrial
food producers,
has given up breeding turkeys
and has lost

13:37.884 --> 13:40.653 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
money because of E.U. rules
governing slaughtering.

13:40.687 --> 13:44.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KARON SAUNDERS, Organic Farmer:
I don't want
people's employment rights, I
don't want their

13:45.024 --> 13:50.830 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
human rights changed. I don't
want that to
be lessened. And I don't think
it will.

13:50.863 --> 13:59.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What I do want is to be able to
look at legislation
in a realistic manner. We may be
able to put

13:59.238 --> 14:06.145 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the small slaughter houses,
have that working
for us, rather than working
against us. Why

14:06.179 --> 14:12.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
do we need a vet to stand over
people who
for centuries have always killed
the animals

14:12.518 --> 14:16.823 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
usually at the back of the
butcher's or at
home? There are legislations and
there are

14:16.856 --> 14:20.827 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ways that we can work that our
standards don't
drop.

14:20.860 --> 14:23.629 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
LINDA DUFFIN, Financial
Journalist: I do think
a lot of Brexiters have
essentially got their

14:23.663 --> 14:28.668 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fingers in their ears and they
are going la,
la, la, la, la, because if we
leave Europe,

14:28.701 --> 14:30.803 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on what terms do we then do
business with
Europe?

14:30.837 --> 14:35.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Mrs. Portly has
spoken. That's
the name financial journalist
Linda Duffin

14:35.575 --> 14:37.910 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
uses when she blogs about food.

14:37.944 --> 14:42.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LINDA DUFFIN: My concerns are
the potential
for a drop in trade and investor
uncertainty.

14:42.915 --> 14:48.788 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you look at the figures, 42
percent of
our exports are to the E.U., 48
percent of

14:48.821 --> 14:54.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
our foreign direct trade is from
the E.U.
Essentially, if we leave the
E.U., we will

14:54.060 --> 15:00.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have to toe the line, but we
won't have any
say in where that line is drawn.

15:00.333 --> 15:05.037 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NARRATOR: Every week, the United
Kingdom sends
350 million pounds of taxpayers
money to the

15:05.071 --> 15:12.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
E.U. That's the cost of a fully
staffed brand-new
hospital.

15:12.145 --> 15:16.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GORDON BROWN, Former British
Prime Minister:
I'm walking through the remains
of Coventry

15:16.849 --> 15:24.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Cathedral, bombed and destroyed
by Nazi warplanes
75 years ago, and now
painstakingly and lovingly

15:24.056 --> 15:29.762 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
maintained as a monument to wars
that we have
left behind and to the sanctuary
of peace.

15:29.796 --> 15:33.900 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what message would we send
to the rest
of the world if we, the British
people, the

15:33.933 --> 15:40.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
most internationally minded of
all, were to
walk away from our nearest
neighbors? We should

15:40.072 --> 15:42.942 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
be leading in Europe, and not
leaving it.

15:42.975 --> 15:47.647 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Nostalgia for
Britain's fighting
spirit during the Second World
War is never

15:47.680 --> 15:54.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
far away at Frinton-on-Sea,
where a portrait
of Winston Churchill adorns the
railway station.

15:54.320 --> 16:00.693 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Frinton, a bastion of gentility
and snobbishness,
has frequently rebelled against
convention

16:00.726 --> 16:05.531 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
and common causes. When
Churchill promised
that Britain would fight
Hitler's Germany

16:05.565 --> 16:08.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on the beaches, there was the
following response.

16:08.034 --> 16:13.172 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS OPPERMAN, Frinton-on-Sea:
Frinton Parish
Council cabled Whitehall and
said, "Not on

16:13.206 --> 16:14.974 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
our beaches, you're not."

16:15.007 --> 16:16.742 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

16:16.776 --> 16:20.079 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: A Second World
War machine
gun nest is part of the fabric
of Frinton

16:20.112 --> 16:25.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Station, and for the remain
campaign symbolizes
the bunker mentality of the
Brexiters.

16:25.585 --> 16:31.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Chris Opperman, a former pig
farmer and broadcaster,
was going to vote to remain, but
changed his

16:31.057 --> 16:32.892 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
mind.

16:32.925 --> 16:37.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRIS OPPERMAN: I believe
England is better
off by itself, because we have
the drive and

16:37.463 --> 16:47.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tenacity to make up for any of
the so-called
benefits. I believe the
engineering powerhouse

16:47.506 --> 16:50.476 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
is still locked away somewhere
in Britain.

16:50.509 --> 16:59.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have been inspired by some
impassioned speeches
by employers of small factories,
major employers

16:59.485 --> 17:06.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as well, who've said, we can get
on, we don't
have to have the -- what they
call the feather

17:06.859 --> 17:09.295 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
bed of Europe to push our
exports.

17:09.328 --> 17:13.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: during the
course of this
campaign, the lead has changed
hands. According

17:13.666 --> 17:17.536 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to the latest opinion polls,
though, both
sides are running neck and neck.

17:17.570 --> 17:21.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But during recent campaigns,
such surveys
have been proved to be fallible,
because people

17:21.908 --> 17:30.683 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have sought to mislead the
pollsters. And
so it's far too risky to predict
the outcome.

17:30.716 --> 17:35.354 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Watching from the sidelines as
Britain tears
itself apart are immigrants from
Eastern Europe,

17:35.388 --> 17:40.259 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
who're concerned about a
campaign that some
say featured a xenophobic edge.
These are

17:40.293 --> 17:43.829 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
some of the 5,000 Poles who live
in Ipswich.

17:43.863 --> 17:45.665 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Student Julia Rusek:

17:45.698 --> 17:54.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JULIA RUSEK, Polish Student:
It's quite hurtful
that people like me get blamed
for things

17:54.206 --> 17:59.478 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like the fall of the -- the fall
the England.
And apparently we're stealing
the jobs that

17:59.512 --> 18:04.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
other English people could do.
We want to
give back to the country that
gave us education.

18:04.317 --> 18:09.021 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We want to -- when I grow up,
after I finish
university, I want to be paying
my taxes,

18:09.055 --> 18:13.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I want to be paying all of my
bills. The way
I was brought up was to give
back to the -- to

18:13.993 --> 18:15.828 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
people that give to me.

18:15.861 --> 18:20.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: The campaign
has also generated
quiet despair in Professor
Stephen Bazire,

18:20.833 --> 18:26.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a leading pharmacist, his hobby,
railway modeling.
He believes Prime Minister David
Cameron's

18:26.372 --> 18:31.177 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pledge to hold the referendum
was a mistake
that could lead to the breakup
of the United

18:31.210 --> 18:33.012 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Kingdom.

18:33.045 --> 18:37.283 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STEPHEN BAZIRE, Pharmacist: I'm
quite worried
that there will be a lot of
vindictiveness

18:37.316 --> 18:44.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going around between pros and
antis. And I
don't see Britain becoming at
all united as

18:44.290 --> 18:49.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a result of this, because if the
result is
very close, then you will have
people who

18:49.095 --> 18:52.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
really are quite worried about
staying in
Europe and people who are quite
worried about

18:52.498 --> 18:55.901 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
leaving Europe, and will be
blaming each other.

18:55.935 --> 19:00.840 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Scotland will probably then
go for another
referendum and will probably
leave. Wales

19:00.873 --> 19:07.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
might well do the same. And I
think we become
little Englanders then, again,
rather than

19:07.380 --> 19:09.615 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
being part of a wider community.

19:09.648 --> 19:15.321 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MALCOLM BRABANT: Only the voters
can now decide
whether the Brexit express is a
runaway train

19:15.354 --> 19:21.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that may lead to the shrinking
of world's
fifth largest economy. If
Britain votes leave,

19:21.093 --> 19:26.232 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there can be no turning back,
and no one seems
to know what the consequences
will be.

19:26.265 --> 19:33.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
For the "PBS NewsHour," this is
Malcolm Brabant
in East Anglia.

19:33.239 --> 19:46.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: The American
middle class is
shrinking and struggling. The
six-year-long

19:46.285 --> 19:51.357 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
economic recovery is showing
some signs of
slowing. And the pronounced
wealth divide

19:51.390 --> 19:54.927 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in the U.S. may get worse
without bigger steps.

19:54.960 --> 20:00.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That warning was part of a new
report issued
today about the U.S. economy by
the International

20:00.099 --> 20:02.034 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Monetary Fund.

20:02.068 --> 20:06.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I sat down with its managing
director, Christine
Lagarde, at IMF headquarters
here in Washington

20:06.972 --> 20:11.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
earlier today to hear more of
her concerns
about what's happening to the
middle class

20:11.644 --> 20:15.481 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and the poor, and what could be
done about
it.

20:15.514 --> 20:18.150 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Managing Director Christine
Lagarde, thank
you for talking with us.

20:18.184 --> 20:19.985 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTINE LAGARDE, Managing
Director, International
Monetary Fund: Pleasure.

20:20.019 --> 20:23.789 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, this latest
report from
the IMF looks at the American
economy, says

20:23.823 --> 20:30.162 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it is in good shape overall,
shows resiliency,
but then it goes on to point out
a number

20:30.196 --> 20:34.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of factors that provide concern
for the future.

20:34.667 --> 20:39.238 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And one of them has to do with
the shrinkage
of the American middle class.
What do you

20:39.271 --> 20:42.408 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and your colleagues see, and
what concerns
you?

20:42.441 --> 20:46.178 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTINE LAGARDE: We are seeing
a shrinking
of the middle class.

20:46.212 --> 20:52.318 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If you look at the size of the
middle class
in 1975, it was roughly 60
percent of total

20:52.351 --> 20:58.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
population. If you look at the
middle class
today, it is about 50 percent.
So, that's

20:58.124 --> 21:05.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a significant decline of the
middle class.
And it is an economic issue,
because the middle

21:05.898 --> 21:11.871 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
class has always been the
consumption force
of this nation.

21:11.904 --> 21:19.211 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The upper class doesn't spend as
much. The
lower class doesn't have as much
to spend.

21:19.245 --> 21:25.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the maximum impact in terms
of consumption
is generated by the middle
class.

21:25.084 --> 21:29.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What's happening
here? You
also write in the report your
concern about

21:29.889 --> 21:37.163 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the so-called labor force
participation rate,
the number of people who are
actually working.

21:37.196 --> 21:43.169 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we know that there is
concern about the
number of men and women who are
able to find

21:43.202 --> 21:45.004 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
a job. What do you see there?

21:45.037 --> 21:52.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTINE LAGARDE: What we are
seeing is something
that affects us all, which is
aging.

21:52.912 --> 21:58.684 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The U.S. population is aging,
like in other
economies of the world, and, as
a result,

21:58.717 --> 22:08.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the participation of active
workers in the
economy is declining. Now, we
cannot stop

22:08.360 --> 22:14.433 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the course of time, but what
policies can
do is encourage people who are
not joining

22:14.466 --> 22:19.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the workplace, the job market,
to actually
do so.

22:19.371 --> 22:26.979 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I would point to a couple of
policies.
One is support given to women.
And, by that,

22:27.012 --> 22:35.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean maternity leave policy
that would help
them face the decision of, do I
stay or do

22:35.721 --> 22:43.762 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I go? Second, child care
support, and not
just child actually, but the
kind of support

22:43.796 --> 22:51.170 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that would help families look
after a child
or look after an elderly,
because, with aging,

22:51.203 --> 22:54.873 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we will have to support more
parents or grandparents.

22:54.907 --> 22:59.878 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you're
describing a real
squeeze on the middle class in
this country.

22:59.912 --> 23:04.350 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTINE LAGARDE: Yes, there is
that squeeze.
And that's where you head in the
directions

23:04.383 --> 23:09.888 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of people feeling insecure,
people not wanting
to move from one job to the
other, people

23:09.922 --> 23:13.092 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
not spending as much as they
would otherwise
do.

23:13.125 --> 23:18.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Those behaviors, those decisions
have an economic
impact on our growth.

23:18.731 --> 23:22.001 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Help us
understand, what's
the connection with the overall
economy?

23:22.034 --> 23:27.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTINE LAGARDE: Well, the
major engine
for growth in this country and
in quite a

23:27.406 --> 23:32.111 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
few advanced economies as well
is typically
consumption.

23:32.144 --> 23:39.585 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When the U.S. consumer consumes,
there is
demand, more demand, and,
therefore, the U.S.

23:39.618 --> 23:44.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
manufacturers must manufacture
more. If they
have to manufacture more, they
have to create

23:44.390 --> 23:51.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more jobs. It's a fairly simple
virtuous circle
that is generally initiated by
consumption.

23:51.964 --> 23:56.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A number of
remedies you lay
out would cost money. They would
require action

23:56.969 --> 24:03.842 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by the Congress at a time when
this country
is very politically polarized.
How realistic

24:03.876 --> 24:06.512 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
do you think your
recommendations are at a
time like this?

24:06.545 --> 24:11.517 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTINE LAGARDE: I see one
area where there
