27:28.914 --> 27:36.188 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
efforts for more racially
integrated classrooms;
and a plea to adopt the metric
system in the

27:36.221 --> 27:38.056 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
U.S.

27:38.090 --> 27:42.327 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first: The president and
Congress have
reached rare agreement on a new
law that will

27:42.361 --> 27:48.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
regulate everyday toxic
chemicals. The president
signed it today, setting in
motion the biggest

27:48.433 --> 27:50.302 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
changes in four decades.

27:50.335 --> 27:55.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Environmental Protection
Agency now has
new authority to review and
eventually restrict

27:55.807 --> 28:01.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or ban tens of thousands of
chemicals that
could be carcinogenic or
otherwise harm human

28:02.014 --> 28:07.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
health, among them, substances
found in household
detergents and cleansers, flame
retardants

28:07.753 --> 28:09.421 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and furniture.

28:09.454 --> 28:11.089 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
But it may take a while.

28:11.123 --> 28:13.392 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lisa Desjardins joins us to fill
in the picture.

28:13.425 --> 28:15.394 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Lisa, why is this significant?

28:15.427 --> 28:17.663 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: This is
incredibly significant.

28:17.696 --> 28:22.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're talking about a vast
universe of things
that we touch in our everyday
lives. Some

28:22.768 --> 28:27.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
estimate that one out of every
three sort
of processed products that we
buy, not food,

28:27.573 --> 28:30.242 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but everything else, could have
toxic chemicals
in it.

28:30.275 --> 28:35.080 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what happened, Gwen, was the
law passed
40 years ago was essentially
toothless. So

28:35.113 --> 28:41.086 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the EPA wasn't even able to
regulate forcefully
something like asbestos, which
we know from

28:41.119 --> 28:45.991 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
scientific evidence is lethal
and may -- causes
a lethal form of cancer, but yet
it's not

28:46.024 --> 28:49.328 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
banned because the law
previously wasn't strong
enough.

28:49.361 --> 28:53.065 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You and I both have
covered Washington
for a while. We know how hard it
is to get

28:53.098 --> 28:56.234 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
bipartisan agreement on
anything. Why this,
why now?

28:56.268 --> 28:56.668 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Imagine.

28:56.702 --> 28:58.503 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
GWEN IFILL: Wow.

28:58.537 --> 29:00.939 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: Nothing is
getting done in
Washington. A sweeping bill over
an $800 billion

29:00.973 --> 29:04.176 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
industry? Well, that's the
answer. The industry
got on board.

29:04.209 --> 29:09.081 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The chemical industry felt this
was in their
interest because, up until now,
they have

29:09.114 --> 29:14.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
self-regulated and states have
regulated,
Gwen. So the chemical industry
has dealt with

29:14.519 --> 29:19.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
50 different sets of laws across
this country.
They found that it was in their
interest at

29:19.291 --> 29:22.995 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this time to have a national
law, have the
EPA take this over.

29:23.028 --> 29:27.699 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So what we're going to have now
from this
law is the EPA having dominance,
being able

29:27.733 --> 29:31.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to override states, with some
exceptions,
in general when it comes to
chemical safety.

29:31.970 --> 29:34.539 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: There are so many
different arguments
on either side of this.

29:34.573 --> 29:36.308 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Yes.

29:36.341 --> 29:39.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: One is that this is
the best it
could get and this is a strong,
big move.

29:39.978 --> 29:41.013 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What is the argument for that?

29:41.046 --> 29:42.781 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LISA DESJARDINS: Right.

29:42.814 --> 29:46.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So let's talk about supporters.
They feel
like this was something that was
a long time

29:46.218 --> 29:50.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coming, that these are dangerous
chemicals
that are unregulated and could
explain things

29:50.689 --> 29:55.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
like, oh, autism or cancer. We
don't know
if they do, but the question is,
no one is

29:55.761 --> 29:57.963 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
investigating. Now the EPA can
investigate.

29:57.996 --> 30:03.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So that group includes people
like Tom Udall
of New Mexico. And he spoke to
us about this

30:03.135 --> 30:04.870 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
law.

30:04.903 --> 30:07.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REP. TOM UDALL (D), New Mexico:
The first
thing to realize, we're doing
zero today.

30:07.639 --> 30:13.645 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're not doing any chemicals
today. And so
what this bill does is stand up
the agency

30:13.679 --> 30:17.582 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to get working in a really
constructive way
on chemicals.

30:17.616 --> 30:22.688 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are going to be many
chemicals, and
that's why I think many
chemicals that aren't

30:22.721 --> 30:27.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
addressed in the first couple
years, and that's
why I would urge the states to
get out there

30:27.893 --> 30:29.628 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
and to regulate.

30:29.661 --> 30:33.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: And yet, Lisa, there
are people
who don't think that this goes
far enough,

30:33.632 --> 30:36.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not only members of Congress,
but a lot of
people involved in activist
groups.

30:36.902 --> 30:40.706 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: That's right.
This bill tried
to address a problem of scale,
but it has

30:40.739 --> 30:42.507 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a problem of scale.

30:42.541 --> 30:46.011 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Let's look at a graphic
explaining this. As
we mentioned earlier in this
segment, there

30:46.044 --> 30:50.882 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
