the EPA has
yet to review and now can
review. But the

30:50.916 --> 30:57.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
problem is how long it takes to
do that. Under
this law, the EPA is required to
examine at

30:57.355 --> 31:01.159 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
least 20 of those chemicals
within a four-year
time span.

31:01.193 --> 31:05.597 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That gives you a sense of how
long it takes
to go through each of these
chemicals. And

31:05.630 --> 31:09.234 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
some who are nervous about this
bill say,
realistically, we're in the sure
this is even

31:09.267 --> 31:12.304 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
going to scratch the surface of
the problem.

31:12.337 --> 31:15.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Someone who has those questions
is Scott Faber
with the Environmental Working
Group. He talked

31:15.707 --> 31:17.442 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to us for this story.

31:17.476 --> 31:20.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SCOTT FABER, Environmental
Working Group:
The bill provides half as much
money as the

31:20.278 --> 31:25.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
agency needs just to get through
the thousand
most dangerous chemicals out of
many thousands

31:26.017 --> 31:28.453 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of chemicals that are used in
commerce.

31:28.487 --> 31:33.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Certainly, if you ask the
question, is this
law better than what we have on
the books,

31:33.091 --> 31:38.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the answer is yes. If you ask
the question,
does this law give EPA the
ability to quickly

31:38.363 --> 31:42.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
review and regulate the most
dangerous chemicals,
the answer is almost certainly
no.

31:42.768 --> 31:48.774 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: That's not the most
enthusiastic
-- in fact, not criticism or
endorsement.

31:48.807 --> 31:52.644 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LISA DESJARDINS: And yet groups
like this
still signed on, because they
feel like this

31:52.677 --> 31:55.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is better than nothing, which is
exactly what
you heard.

31:55.247 --> 31:59.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think it's because this is
sort of an
invisible problem. When we say
this is a huge

31:59.885 --> 32:05.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
amount of products, it's a vast
number of
products, baby bottles, car
seats, mattresses.

32:05.323 --> 32:08.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Even, Gwen, something like the
necklace I'm
wearing right now, I know you
will be shocked

32:08.660 --> 32:13.865 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
